  "prompt": "What are the differences between single board computer and microcontroller?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between Single Board Computers (SBCs) and Microcontrollers:\n\nSingle Board Computers (SBCs):\n1. Full computer system on a single board\n2. Run full operating systems (Linux, Android)\n3. Higher processing power\n4. More RAM (typically 1-8 GB)\n5. Multiple core processors\n6. Higher clock speeds\n7. Complex software development\n8. Higher power consumption\n9. More expensive\n10. Examples: Raspberry Pi, BeagleBone\n11. Better for complex computing tasks\n12. Have USB, HDMI, network interfaces\n13. Can run multiple applications simultaneously\n\nMicrocontrollers:\n1. Compact integrated circuit\n2. Run simple real-time operating systems or bare metal programming\n3. Lower processing power\n4. Limited RAM (few kilobytes)\n5. Single or limited core processors\n6. Lower clock speeds\n7. Simpler programming\n8. Low power consumption\n9. Less expensive\n10. Examples: Arduino, ESP32\n11. Ideal for embedded systems and specific tasks\n12. Limited peripheral interfaces\n13. Focus on specific hardware control\n14. Real-time processing capabilities\n15. Direct hardware interaction\n\nChoosing between them depends on project complexity, processing requirements, and budget.",
